#let images = (
  "10.1": (
    caption: [Light and carbon reactions of photosynthesis in chloroplasts of land plants. In thylakoid membranes, the excitation of chlorophyll in the photosynthetic electron transport system (photosystem II + photosystem I) by light drives the synthesis of ATP and NADPH. These energy-rich compounds power the Calvin-Benson cycle in the chloroplast stroma, where atmospheric CO2 is converted to triose phosphates and other organic compounds.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "10.2": (
    caption: [The Calvin-Benson cycle proceeds in three phases: (1) carboxylation, which covalently links atmospheric carbon (CO2) to a carbon skeleton; (2) reduction, which forms a carbohydrate (triose phosphate) at the expense of NADPH and ATP; and (3) regeneration, which reforms the CO2 acceptor molecule ribulose 1,5-bisphosphate.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "10.3": (
    caption: [Calvin-Benson cycle showing the carboxylation of three molecules of ribulose 1,5-bisphosphate yielding six molecules of 3-phosphoglycerate (carboxylation phase). After phosphorylation of the carboxyl group, 1,3-bisphosphoglycerate is reduced to glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate (reduction phase). Five molecules of glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate are used to regenerate three molecules of ribulose 1,5-bisphosphate (regeneration phase), and one molecule is used for biosynthetic processes.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "10.4": (
    caption: [Carboxylation and oxygenation of ribulose 1,5-bisphosphate catalyzed by Rubisco. The binding of ribulose 1,5-bisphosphate to Rubisco facilitates the formation of an enzyme-bound enediol intermediate that can be attacked by CO2 or O2 at carbon 2. With CO2, the product is a six-carbon intermediate that splits into two molecules of 3-phosphoglycerate. With O2, the product splits into one molecule of 3-phosphoglycerate and one molecule of 2-phosphoglycolate.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "10.5": (
    caption: [CO2 functions as both an activator and a substrate in the reaction catalyzed by Rubisco. Rubisco activation requires the reaction of activator CO2 with the enzyme to form an unstable carbamate adduct. Mg2+ binding stabilizes the active site. The activated Rubisco then binds the substrate ribulose 1,5-bisphosphate and catalyzes the addition of substrate CO2 to form two molecules of 3-phosphoglycerate.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "10.6": (
    caption: [Ferredoxin-thioredoxin system links the redox status of the thylakoid membranes to the activity of enzymes in the chloroplast stroma. The activation of Calvin-Benson cycle enzymes starts in the light with the reduction of ferredoxin by the photosynthetic electron transport chain. Reduced ferredoxin transfers electrons to thioredoxin via ferredoxin-thioredoxin reductase. Reduced thioredoxin activates target enzymes by reducing disulfide bonds.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "10.7": (
    caption: [Regulation of chloroplast phosphoribulokinase and glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate dehydrogenase. Chloroplasts contain two isoforms of glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate dehydrogenases (A4 and A2B2). The A and B polypeptides form heterotetramers that undergo redox regulation. Light-dependent reduction of disulfide bridges activates these enzymes, while oxidation in the dark inactivates them.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "10.8": (
    caption: [Operation of photorespiration showing enzymatic reactions distributed in three organelles: chloroplasts, peroxisomes, and mitochondria. In chloroplasts, the oxygenase activity of Rubisco produces 2-phosphoglycolate. The photorespiratory pathway recovers carbon from 2-phosphoglycolate through a series of reactions that consume ATP and release CO2 and ammonia.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "10.9": (
    caption: [Dependence of photorespiration on chloroplast metabolism. The supply of ATP and reducing equivalents from light reactions in thylakoid membranes is needed for the functioning of photorespiration in three compartments. Photorespiration requires energy and reducing power from photosynthesis to recycle carbon back to the Calvin-Benson cycle.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "10.10": (
    caption: [The C4 photosynthetic carbon cycle involves five successive stages in two distinct cell types. In mesophyll cells, phosphoenolpyruvate carboxylase (PEPCase) catalyzes the reaction of bicarbonate with phosphoenolpyruvate to form oxaloacetate. The four-carbon acid is then transported to bundle sheath cells where CO2 is released and refixed by Rubisco in the Calvin-Benson cycle.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "10.11": (
    caption: [C4 photosynthetic pathway in leaves of different plants showing Kranz anatomy. This anatomical feature compartmentalizes the initial CO2 fixation (in mesophyll cells) and the Calvin-Benson cycle (in bundle sheath cells). The spatial separation allows C4 plants to concentrate CO2 around Rubisco, reducing photorespiration.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "10.12": (
    caption: [Crassulacean acid metabolism (CAM) in Kalanchoe. In CAM metabolism, CO2 uptake is separated temporally from refixation via the Calvin-Benson cycle. The uptake of atmospheric CO2 takes place at night when stomata are open, and CO2 is stored as malic acid in vacuoles. During the day, stomata close and the stored malic acid is decarboxylated to release CO2 for the Calvin-Benson cycle.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "10.13": (
    caption: [Carbon mobilization in land plants. During the day, carbon assimilated photosynthetically is used either for the formation of starch in the chloroplast or is exported to the cytosol for the synthesis of sucrose. External and internal factors regulate the partitioning of photosynthate between starch and sucrose. At night, starch is degraded to support continued sucrose synthesis.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "10.14": (
    caption: [Composition and structure of the starch granule. Starch is made up of amylose and amylopectin. Glucose units are linked through α-1,4 glycosidic bonds in linear chains. Amylopectin also contains α-1,6 glycosidic bonds at branch points. The arrangement of these polymers creates the semicrystalline structure of starch granules.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "10.15": (
    caption: [Pathway of starch synthesis. Starch biosynthesis in plants is a complex process that includes biosynthesis of the sugar nucleotide ADP-glucose, formation of the primer, elongation of the linear α-1,4-glucan chains, introduction of α-1,6 branch points, and trimming of branches to create the final granule structure.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "10.16": (
    caption: [Nocturnal starch degradation in Arabidopsis leaves. The release of soluble glucans from the starch granule at night requires prior phosphorylation of the polysaccharide via glucan-water dikinases. Debranching enzymes and β-amylases then degrade the phosphorylated starch to maltose and glucose, which are exported to the cytosol for sucrose synthesis.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "10.17": (
    caption: [Interconversion of hexose phosphates. Fructose 1,6-bisphosphate formed from triose phosphates by the action of aldolase has a phosphate group cleaved from the carbon 1 position by cytosolic fructose 1,6-bisphosphatase. The resulting fructose 6-phosphate is isomerized to glucose 6-phosphate and glucose 1-phosphate, which serve as precursors for sucrose synthesis.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "10.18": (
    caption: [Sucrose synthesis. Sucrose 6F-phosphate synthase catalyzes the transfer of the glucosyl moiety from UDP-glucose to fructose 6-phosphate, yielding sucrose 6F-phosphate. Dephosphorylation of sucrose 6F-phosphate by sucrose 6F-phosphate phosphatase produces free sucrose. The synthesis and activity of these enzymes are regulated by metabolites and post-translational modifications.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "10.19": (
    caption: [Glucose 6-phosphate and phosphate regulate the synthesis of sucrose. Glucose 6-phosphate increases the synthesis of sucrose by modulating the activity of two associated enzymes. Glucose 6-phosphate enhances sucrose 6F-phosphate synthase activity and inhibits sucrose 6F-phosphate phosphatase activity, providing coordinated regulation of the sucrose synthesis pathway.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-10.1": (
    caption: [Mechanisms of C4 acid decarboxylation in bundle sheath cells showing the three types of C4 photosynthesis based on the decarboxylating enzyme and subcellular localization. Different C4 plants use different four-carbon acids and decarboxylation enzymes (NADP-malic enzyme, NAD-malic enzyme, or phosphoenolpyruvate carboxykinase) in different compartments.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
)
